issue.title: File target archive compression goes out of control if log file is held open by other process

labels.name: file-archiving
labels.description: Issues with archiving with the file target

issue.body:
**Type** (choose one): Bug

**NLog version**: 4.1.0 and 4.3.0-beta3

**Platform**: .Net 4.5, Windows 10

**Current NLog config** (xml or C#, if relevant)

``` xml
  <targets>
    <default-wrapper xsi:type="AsyncWrapper"/>
    ...
    <target name="file" xsi:type="File" layout="${commonLayoutIndented}" 
            fileName="${configFolder}/MediaService.log" 
            createDirs="true" concurrentWrites="false" keepFileOpen="true"
            archiveNumbering="DateAndSequence" archiveDateFormat="yyyy.MM.dd"
            archiveAboveSize="52428800" maxArchiveFiles="10"
            archiveFileName="${configFolder}/MediaService.log.{#}.zip"
            enableArchiveFileCompression="true"
            encoding="UTF-8"/>
  </targets>
```

(${configFolder} is under C:/ProgramData/)

**Description**: We were experimenting with enableArchiveFileCompression. The above file target works wonderfully if the log files are left alone. We were also testing using tail from the Git for Windows installation (portable version also works, both available at https://git-scm.com/download/win) to watch our log file. When the rollover limit was hit, the log file stopped growing, and several empty archive files started rapidly being created and rolling over, very similar to what is described in #1028 (but we have concurrentWrites="false"). When we stopped the tail process, it seems to recover.

We tried updating to 4.3.0-beta3 since #1028 was fixed for that release, and with that version, it instead just stops logging, creates a single archive, and then nothing happens (no further log messages anywhere), until we stop tail, then it will continue as if nothing happened (spamming all the buffered log events so far to disk).

Tail is probably not the only program that triggers this, but I won't speculate on how tail is opening the file (or what NLog actually does when it rotates/archives the file). It's just a concrete program that can reproduce this.

Nothing special from the internal nlog log, for 4.1.0 we get nothing at all, and from 4.3.0-beta3 we get a single line: 2016-03-18 16:49:42.8018 Info Archiving ...\MediaService.log to zip-archive ...\MediaService.log.2016.03.18.0.zip

Possible workarounds: Don't use stupid tail from Git for Windows :P

On a more serious note, if we remove enableArchiveFileCompression, there are no problems for either version, and archiving and rotation works as expected (tail won't see the new log, but that's its problem)

issue.title: Modifications to header context menu (OnContextMenuHeader)
issue.body:
I would like to add two items to the context menu that is displayed when right-clicking the column headers:

 - Size Column to Fit
 - Size All Columns to Fit

These are copied from the items that Windows Explorer has in its context menu when right-clicking on one of its column headers, and they will behave the same way:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5993051/197331420-5f3366fb-b882-49c6-8982-fefb15b391fd.png)

This issue is *not* asking for the code to be written—it is asking for feedback on the implementation before *I* write code that may end up rejected or lingering forever in a PR.

**Issues/Topics for Discussion:**

1. I want these items to appear at the very top of the context menu, just like they do in Windows. However, that may be considered a breaking change. Would it be accepted if I inserted these items at the top of the context menu (by modifying `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()`), followed by a separator?

2. Assuming that I were to do that, would it be preferred that I shift the indices of the existing items (which are numbered 1, 2, and 3) *down*, so that the new items are numbered 1 and 2? Or would it be preferred that I assign the new items indices 4 and 5, even though they will be inserted in the menu *above* item index 1?

3. Should the automatic insertion of these items be configurable by the client of the control, as with `CGridListCtrlEx::HasColumnEditor()`? Personally, I am thinking that they should always be inserted for all grid controls, so I would be inclined not to add the complexity, but I am open to doing more work if it would increase the odds of the PR getting accepted. Or, you know, if someone has a logical counter-argument. :-)

4. If you don't like *any* of these ideas, then I will need to figure out alternatives (because I really am that stubborn). Unfortunately, the only option available to me now, without modifying the code, is to override the `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()` function, not call the base-class implementation, and handle *everything* myself. I'd rather not do that, as I like most of the default implementation. But I have no way to *customize* the default implementation, since it creates the menu, shows it, and handles its commands all in the same function.

    As a compromise, I could modify the `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()` function to call a new `protected` member function (something like `OnPrepareContextMenuHeader()`) immediately before it shows the context menu (with `TrackPopupMenu()`). I could pass a non-const (mutable) reference to the `CMenu` object (`menu`) to this member function so that derived classes could customize the menu in whatever way they want before it is displayed. Of course, I'd still need to figure out how derived classes could handle selection of the items that they add. This is why I'd rather not do it this way.

**Advice? Suggestions?**

comment.body:
My response:
- `1)` - Think extending OnContextMenuHeader is fine, so it always includes the 2 new options. Extend it for both `CGridListCtrlEx` + `CGridListCtrlGroups`
- `2)` - Think the 2 new options should be on top. Similar to what is done in `CGridListCtrlGroups::OnContextMenuHeader` (Where grouping is on top)
- `3)` - Think the insertion should be controlled by calling a virtual method (one for each item), and each method should also return the menu-item-name. Similar to what is done in `HasColumnDefaultState`

issue.title: ReplaceNewLinesLayoutRendererWrapper fail if replacement contains new line char
issue.body:
**NLog version**: 5.0.4
**Platform**: all

My goal is to align multi line error message.

For example this:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1
MESSAGE LINE 2
```

Became this:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1
                                       | MESSAGE LINE 2
```

The [replace-newlines](https://github.com/NLog/NLog/wiki/Replace-NewLines-Layout-Renderer) renderer is a good candidate.

I tried:
```xml
<variable name="pretty" value="${replace-newlines:replacement=\r\n                                       | :${layout}}" />
```

- What is the current result?

The replacement method is called twice, hence, inserted newlines are re-replaced.
https://github.com/NLog/NLog/blob/6f246d36ee4b796bed15061d8cae9deb4fdc8f86/src/NLog/LayoutRenderers/Wrappers/ReplaceNewLinesLayoutRendererWrapper.cs#L68-L70

The actual result is:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1

                                       |                                        | MESSAGE LINE 2
```

- What is the expected result?

The replacement method should be called once (at least with the replacement string).

- A workaround is to replace Windows new lines to Unix new lines, then replace all new lines by the replacement string:

```C#
string str = builder.ToString(orgLength, builder.Length - orgLength)
                    .Replace(WindowsNewLine, UnixNewLine)
                    .Replace(UnixNewLine, Replacement);
```

issue.title: File target archive compression goes out of control if log file is held open by other process

labels.name: file-archiving
labels.description: Issues with archiving with the file target

issue.body:
**Type** (choose one): Bug

**NLog version**: 4.1.0 and 4.3.0-beta3

**Platform**: .Net 4.5, Windows 10

**Current NLog config** (xml or C#, if relevant)

``` xml
  <targets>
    <default-wrapper xsi:type="AsyncWrapper"/>
    ...
    <target name="file" xsi:type="File" layout="${commonLayoutIndented}" 
            fileName="${configFolder}/MediaService.log" 
            createDirs="true" concurrentWrites="false" keepFileOpen="true"
            archiveNumbering="DateAndSequence" archiveDateFormat="yyyy.MM.dd"
            archiveAboveSize="52428800" maxArchiveFiles="10"
            archiveFileName="${configFolder}/MediaService.log.{#}.zip"
            enableArchiveFileCompression="true"
            encoding="UTF-8"/>
  </targets>
```

(${configFolder} is under C:/ProgramData/)

**Description**: We were experimenting with enableArchiveFileCompression. The above file target works wonderfully if the log files are left alone. We were also testing using tail from the Git for Windows installation (portable version also works, both available at https://git-scm.com/download/win) to watch our log file. When the rollover limit was hit, the log file stopped growing, and several empty archive files started rapidly being created and rolling over, very similar to what is described in #1028 (but we have concurrentWrites="false"). When we stopped the tail process, it seems to recover.

We tried updating to 4.3.0-beta3 since #1028 was fixed for that release, and with that version, it instead just stops logging, creates a single archive, and then nothing happens (no further log messages anywhere), until we stop tail, then it will continue as if nothing happened (spamming all the buffered log events so far to disk).

Tail is probably not the only program that triggers this, but I won't speculate on how tail is opening the file (or what NLog actually does when it rotates/archives the file). It's just a concrete program that can reproduce this.

Nothing special from the internal nlog log, for 4.1.0 we get nothing at all, and from 4.3.0-beta3 we get a single line: 2016-03-18 16:49:42.8018 Info Archiving ...\MediaService.log to zip-archive ...\MediaService.log.2016.03.18.0.zip

Possible workarounds: Don't use stupid tail from Git for Windows :P

On a more serious note, if we remove enableArchiveFileCompression, there are no problems for either version, and archiving and rotation works as expected (tail won't see the new log, but that's its problem)

issue.title: Modifications to header context menu (OnContextMenuHeader)
issue.body:
I would like to add two items to the context menu that is displayed when right-clicking the column headers:

 - Size Column to Fit
 - Size All Columns to Fit

These are copied from the items that Windows Explorer has in its context menu when right-clicking on one of its column headers, and they will behave the same way:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5993051/197331420-5f3366fb-b882-49c6-8982-fefb15b391fd.png)

This issue is *not* asking for the code to be written—it is asking for feedback on the implementation before *I* write code that may end up rejected or lingering forever in a PR.

**Issues/Topics for Discussion:**

1. I want these items to appear at the very top of the context menu, just like they do in Windows. However, that may be considered a breaking change. Would it be accepted if I inserted these items at the top of the context menu (by modifying `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()`), followed by a separator?

2. Assuming that I were to do that, would it be preferred that I shift the indices of the existing items (which are numbered 1, 2, and 3) *down*, so that the new items are numbered 1 and 2? Or would it be preferred that I assign the new items indices 4 and 5, even though they will be inserted in the menu *above* item index 1?

3. Should the automatic insertion of these items be configurable by the client of the control, as with `CGridListCtrlEx::HasColumnEditor()`? Personally, I am thinking that they should always be inserted for all grid controls, so I would be inclined not to add the complexity, but I am open to doing more work if it would increase the odds of the PR getting accepted. Or, you know, if someone has a logical counter-argument. :-)

4. If you don't like *any* of these ideas, then I will need to figure out alternatives (because I really am that stubborn). Unfortunately, the only option available to me now, without modifying the code, is to override the `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()` function, not call the base-class implementation, and handle *everything* myself. I'd rather not do that, as I like most of the default implementation. But I have no way to *customize* the default implementation, since it creates the menu, shows it, and handles its commands all in the same function.

    As a compromise, I could modify the `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()` function to call a new `protected` member function (something like `OnPrepareContextMenuHeader()`) immediately before it shows the context menu (with `TrackPopupMenu()`). I could pass a non-const (mutable) reference to the `CMenu` object (`menu`) to this member function so that derived classes could customize the menu in whatever way they want before it is displayed. Of course, I'd still need to figure out how derived classes could handle selection of the items that they add. This is why I'd rather not do it this way.

**Advice? Suggestions?**

comment.body:
My response:
- `1)` - Think extending OnContextMenuHeader is fine, so it always includes the 2 new options. Extend it for both `CGridListCtrlEx` + `CGridListCtrlGroups`
- `2)` - Think the 2 new options should be on top. Similar to what is done in `CGridListCtrlGroups::OnContextMenuHeader` (Where grouping is on top)
- `3)` - Think the insertion should be controlled by calling a virtual method (one for each item), and each method should also return the menu-item-name. Similar to what is done in `HasColumnDefaultState`

issue.title: ReplaceNewLinesLayoutRendererWrapper fail if replacement contains new line char
issue.body:
**NLog version**: 5.0.4
**Platform**: all

My goal is to align multi line error message.

For example this:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1
MESSAGE LINE 2
```

Became this:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1
                                       | MESSAGE LINE 2
```

The [replace-newlines](https://github.com/NLog/NLog/wiki/Replace-NewLines-Layout-Renderer) renderer is a good candidate.

I tried:
```xml
<variable name="pretty" value="${replace-newlines:replacement=\r\n                                       | :${layout}}" />
```

- What is the current result?

The replacement method is called twice, hence, inserted newlines are re-replaced.
https://github.com/NLog/NLog/blob/6f246d36ee4b796bed15061d8cae9deb4fdc8f86/src/NLog/LayoutRenderers/Wrappers/ReplaceNewLinesLayoutRendererWrapper.cs#L68-L70

The actual result is:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1

                                       |                                        | MESSAGE LINE 2
```

- What is the expected result?

The replacement method should be called once (at least with the replacement string).

- A workaround is to replace Windows new lines to Unix new lines, then replace all new lines by the replacement string:

```C#
string str = builder.ToString(orgLength, builder.Length - orgLength)
                    .Replace(WindowsNewLine, UnixNewLine)
                    .Replace(UnixNewLine, Replacement);
```

issue.title: File target archive compression goes out of control if log file is held open by other process

labels.name: file-archiving
labels.description: Issues with archiving with the file target

issue.body:
**Type** (choose one): Bug

**NLog version**: 4.1.0 and 4.3.0-beta3

**Platform**: .Net 4.5, Windows 10

**Current NLog config** (xml or C#, if relevant)

``` xml
  <targets>
    <default-wrapper xsi:type="AsyncWrapper"/>
    ...
    <target name="file" xsi:type="File" layout="${commonLayoutIndented}" 
            fileName="${configFolder}/MediaService.log" 
            createDirs="true" concurrentWrites="false" keepFileOpen="true"
            archiveNumbering="DateAndSequence" archiveDateFormat="yyyy.MM.dd"
            archiveAboveSize="52428800" maxArchiveFiles="10"
            archiveFileName="${configFolder}/MediaService.log.{#}.zip"
            enableArchiveFileCompression="true"
            encoding="UTF-8"/>
  </targets>
```

(${configFolder} is under C:/ProgramData/)

**Description**: We were experimenting with enableArchiveFileCompression. The above file target works wonderfully if the log files are left alone. We were also testing using tail from the Git for Windows installation (portable version also works, both available at https://git-scm.com/download/win) to watch our log file. When the rollover limit was hit, the log file stopped growing, and several empty archive files started rapidly being created and rolling over, very similar to what is described in #1028 (but we have concurrentWrites="false"). When we stopped the tail process, it seems to recover.

We tried updating to 4.3.0-beta3 since #1028 was fixed for that release, and with that version, it instead just stops logging, creates a single archive, and then nothing happens (no further log messages anywhere), until we stop tail, then it will continue as if nothing happened (spamming all the buffered log events so far to disk).

Tail is probably not the only program that triggers this, but I won't speculate on how tail is opening the file (or what NLog actually does when it rotates/archives the file). It's just a concrete program that can reproduce this.

Nothing special from the internal nlog log, for 4.1.0 we get nothing at all, and from 4.3.0-beta3 we get a single line: 2016-03-18 16:49:42.8018 Info Archiving ...\MediaService.log to zip-archive ...\MediaService.log.2016.03.18.0.zip

Possible workarounds: Don't use stupid tail from Git for Windows :P

On a more serious note, if we remove enableArchiveFileCompression, there are no problems for either version, and archiving and rotation works as expected (tail won't see the new log, but that's its problem)

issue.title: Modifications to header context menu (OnContextMenuHeader)
issue.body:
I would like to add two items to the context menu that is displayed when right-clicking the column headers:

 - Size Column to Fit
 - Size All Columns to Fit

These are copied from the items that Windows Explorer has in its context menu when right-clicking on one of its column headers, and they will behave the same way:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5993051/197331420-5f3366fb-b882-49c6-8982-fefb15b391fd.png)

This issue is *not* asking for the code to be written—it is asking for feedback on the implementation before *I* write code that may end up rejected or lingering forever in a PR.

**Issues/Topics for Discussion:**

1. I want these items to appear at the very top of the context menu, just like they do in Windows. However, that may be considered a breaking change. Would it be accepted if I inserted these items at the top of the context menu (by modifying `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()`), followed by a separator?

2. Assuming that I were to do that, would it be preferred that I shift the indices of the existing items (which are numbered 1, 2, and 3) *down*, so that the new items are numbered 1 and 2? Or would it be preferred that I assign the new items indices 4 and 5, even though they will be inserted in the menu *above* item index 1?

3. Should the automatic insertion of these items be configurable by the client of the control, as with `CGridListCtrlEx::HasColumnEditor()`? Personally, I am thinking that they should always be inserted for all grid controls, so I would be inclined not to add the complexity, but I am open to doing more work if it would increase the odds of the PR getting accepted. Or, you know, if someone has a logical counter-argument. :-)

4. If you don't like *any* of these ideas, then I will need to figure out alternatives (because I really am that stubborn). Unfortunately, the only option available to me now, without modifying the code, is to override the `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()` function, not call the base-class implementation, and handle *everything* myself. I'd rather not do that, as I like most of the default implementation. But I have no way to *customize* the default implementation, since it creates the menu, shows it, and handles its commands all in the same function.

    As a compromise, I could modify the `CGridListCtrlEx::OnContextMenuHeader()` function to call a new `protected` member function (something like `OnPrepareContextMenuHeader()`) immediately before it shows the context menu (with `TrackPopupMenu()`). I could pass a non-const (mutable) reference to the `CMenu` object (`menu`) to this member function so that derived classes could customize the menu in whatever way they want before it is displayed. Of course, I'd still need to figure out how derived classes could handle selection of the items that they add. This is why I'd rather not do it this way.

**Advice? Suggestions?**

comment.body:
My response:
- `1)` - Think extending OnContextMenuHeader is fine, so it always includes the 2 new options. Extend it for both `CGridListCtrlEx` + `CGridListCtrlGroups`
- `2)` - Think the 2 new options should be on top. Similar to what is done in `CGridListCtrlGroups::OnContextMenuHeader` (Where grouping is on top)
- `3)` - Think the insertion should be controlled by calling a virtual method (one for each item), and each method should also return the menu-item-name. Similar to what is done in `HasColumnDefaultState`

issue.title: ReplaceNewLinesLayoutRendererWrapper fail if replacement contains new line char
issue.body:
**NLog version**: 5.0.4
**Platform**: all

My goal is to align multi line error message.

For example this:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1
MESSAGE LINE 2
```

Became this:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1
                                       | MESSAGE LINE 2
```

The [replace-newlines](https://github.com/NLog/NLog/wiki/Replace-NewLines-Layout-Renderer) renderer is a good candidate.

I tried:
```xml
<variable name="pretty" value="${replace-newlines:replacement=\r\n                                       | :${layout}}" />
```

- What is the current result?

The replacement method is called twice, hence, inserted newlines are re-replaced.
https://github.com/NLog/NLog/blob/6f246d36ee4b796bed15061d8cae9deb4fdc8f86/src/NLog/LayoutRenderers/Wrappers/ReplaceNewLinesLayoutRendererWrapper.cs#L68-L70

The actual result is:
```
2022-09-30 12:57:49.0158|INFO |EMITTER | MESSAGE LINE 1

                                       |                                        | MESSAGE LINE 2
```

- What is the expected result?

The replacement method should be called once (at least with the replacement string).

- A workaround is to replace Windows new lines to Unix new lines, then replace all new lines by the replacement string:

```C#
string str = builder.ToString(orgLength, builder.Length - orgLength)
                    .Replace(WindowsNewLine, UnixNewLine)
                    .Replace(UnixNewLine, Replacement);
```
